         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">It is heard [as follows]: without end these ones constantly arise in the world, ... comparable to the Udumbara-flower,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:pinault1988a"/><citedRange>188-193</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">they become visible in the world. And when they arise, they are the refuge of all the beings in the sufferings.</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… they become manifest in the world. But when they arise, they are a refuge for all beings in [their] sorrows.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>683</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">O lovely one, is this one indeed absolutely alone called the seeker of good for the world? And again, are the other ones not (seekers of good) precisely in this way? </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Tell me that! Then Hastāṅkuśa with clever figure readily says to the king: in [the tune] vanapraveśa</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1954"/><citedRange>90</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>124</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:adams2012a"/><citedRange>27</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(In many eras) the other Buddha-lords of the past numerous as the sand of the Ganges river, with the splendor of the body they have illuminated the three-thousand-fold worlds, </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">in order to see (the salvation) of the Nirvāṇa concerning the gods [and] the humans. These ones make an effort about that which is proper to them, they pull the world out of danger.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... if you learn (something) in a good action, in that case then in every distant other birth the good action will be a lesson for you.               </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... if something (has been learned) by the mind, if one is reborn in a different birth, this indeed becomes a lesson for that (mind).</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">This text shows instances of hypercorrect spellings of diphthongs:</note><note type="remarks">Fragments PK NS 34, <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns37"/> (including 38), <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns144"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns398"/> belong to the same manuscript. In this fragment the right margin is preserved. On both sides traces of ruling are still visible.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">The meter is 4 x 14 syllables with the rhythm 7/7; the name of the tune ought to be restored as <hi>vanapraveś</hi>, loan from Skt. <hi>vanapraveśa-</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="lingcomment"><hi>aum</hi> for <hi>om</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="lingcomment"><hi>alyaik</hi> for <hi>alyek</hi></note><note corresp="#b4" type="lingcomment">Note also the gemination of the initial stop of <hi>ppo</hi> for <hi>po</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
